<a href="#0" id="0">Definition 7</a>
<a href="#1" id="1">A representative-voter rule is an aggregation rule F that is such that for every profile E there exists an individual {a mathematical formula}i ⋆ ∈ N such that {a mathematical formula}F(E)=Ei ⋆ .</a>
<a href="#2" id="2">Definition 19</a>
<a href="#3" id="3">An aggregation rule F is called collectively rational with respect to a graph property P if {a mathematical formula}F(E) satisfies P whenever all of the individual graphs in {a mathematical formula}E=(E1, … ,En) do.</a>
<a href="#4" id="4">Definition 26</a>
<a href="#5" id="5">An aggregation rule F is frame collectively rational with respect to a modal integrity constraint Φ if {a mathematical formula} 〈 V,Ei 〉 ⊨ Φ for all {a mathematical formula}i ∈ N implies {a mathematical formula} 〈 V,F(E) 〉 ⊨ Φ .</a>
<a href="#6" id="6">Definition 27</a>
<a href="#7" id="7">An aggregation rule F is model collectively rational with respect to a modal integrity constraint Φ if for every valuation {a mathematical formula}Val: Φ → 2V we have {a mathematical formula} 〈 〈 V,Ei 〉 ,Val 〉 ⊨ Φ for all {a mathematical formula}i ∈ N implying {a mathematical formula} 〈 〈 V,F(E) 〉 ,Val 〉 ⊨ Φ .</a>
<a href="#8" id="8">Any unanimous aggregation rule is frame collectively rational with respect to {a mathematical formula}p → ◇ p.</a>
